    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nBased on @justinmk's [comment](https://www.reddit.com/r/neovim/comments/1rrmb8n/comment/oa1djgt/?utm_source=share&utm_medium=web3x&utm_name=web3xcss&utm_term=1&utm_content=share_button).\n\nWith `:trust`/`vim.secure.read()`, using `exrc` for project-specific configuration is now a reasonable choice again.\n\nCurrently, if `exrc` is enabled in a user's configuration, the `.exrc` (and `.nvim.lua`, etc.) are loaded after the user configuration has been completely sourced. This behaviour is inherited directly from Vim.\n\nThis means that `exrc` files cannot influence a user's configuration - at most they can attempt to override or undo changes made there. For example, it is currently not really possible to _disable_ the loading of a plugin via the user's plugin manager of choice, as by the time `exrc` is loaded, the plugin manager has usually already run and the plugin has been installed.\n\nIf it were possible to have `exrc` load earlier, this would be significantly easier.\n\nCurrently, to achieve this, I effectively re-implement the `exrc` mechanism directly [in my own configuration](https://github.com/schilkp/dot/blob/d908f074a1506e937eaeec1b1766a666751d8752/neovim/.config/nvim/lua/schilk/local_config/init.lua#L65), allowing my `exrc` files to configure values in the `_G` table which my config then uses. Rough example:\n\n```lua\n-- .exrc.lua:\n_G.EXCLUDE_PLUGINS = {\n    ['neovim/nvim-lspconfig'] = true\n}\n\n-- init.lua:\nlocal plugins = {\n    -- ... list of plugins ...\n}\n\nif _G.EXCLUDE_PLUGINS then\n  plugins = vim.tbl_filter(function(plugin)\n    local name = type(plugin) == \"string\" and plugin or plugin[1]\n    return not _G.EXCLUDE_PLUGINS[name]\n  end, plugins)\nend\n\nrequire(\"lazy\").setup(plugins)\n```\n\nSee my post [here](https://schilk.co/blog/nvim-local-conf/) for more details on this setup.\n\nThis makes `.exrc` files useful for both additive and subtractive changes to my config.\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n\nTo be discussed, a few rough options off the top of my head:\n\n- Make `exrc` greedy, triggering the sourcing as soon as it is set\n    - Downside: breaks compatibility with Vim.\n\n- Introduce a separate option to make `exrc` greedy or not, which can default to off to stay compatible with Vim.\n    - Downside: unclear/possibly confusing semantics, especially regarding ordering?\n      ```vimscript\n      set greedyexrc\n      set exrc \" -> triggers immediate sourcing\n      ```\n\n      ```vimscript\n      set exrc\n      set greedyexrc \" -> should this trigger immediate exrc sourcing?\n      ```\n\n- Make `exrc` accept multiple possible values?\n  ```vimscript\n  set exrc=lazy\n  set exrc=greedy\n  ```\n  - Downside: cleanest interface, but possibly breaks existing configs.\n\nHappy to have a go at implementing this if there is agreement on what the best behaviour should be :)\n\nCheers!",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
