        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> If this would be implemented I would strongly suggest to add a note to the `'exrc'` docs: most people probably want to set `'exrc'` on the last line of their init.lua to not overwrite values there. (which would feel a bit weird to me?).\n\nThinking about this more...\n\nIMO overwriting settings in `exrc` that are previously set in a user config is a super common task, so I am not 100% convinced that having `exrc` load greedily on `set exrc` is a perfect solution, because it requires the user to be extremely explicit about the ordering of how options are set in their config to get the desired effect - this would not be obvious.\n\nEspecially, since the order of config loading gets pretty complicated in modern setups (lazy loading in `lazy`, `now` and `later` in mini.deps...).\n\nFurthermore, it forces the user to choose between using `exrc` files to overwrite settings (by putting `set exrc` towards the end of their config) or pre-loading information that can be used within their config (`set exrc` at the beginning of the config).\n\nMaybe an approach that enables both is better?\n\n`.nvim.lua` vs `.nvim.early.lua`? Or `.nvim.lua` vs `.after.nvim.lua`?\n\nMaybe there should be a seperate option to enable greedy `exrc` loading, which loads different files with different names?\n\nNot sure, but thought I would throw out my thinking.\n",
